Hoisting is the default behaviour of JavaScript where all the variable and function declarations are moved on top.
// Example of Global Scope
hoistedVariable = 3;
console.log(hoistedVariable); // outputs 3 even when the variable is declared after it is initialized   
var hoistedVariable;

// --------------------

// Example of Local Scope
function doSomething(){
  x = 33;
  console.log(x); // Outputs 33 since the local variable “x” is hoisted inside the local scope
  var x;
} 

In JavaScript, both the keywords var and let are used to declare variables.
let is block-scope.
var is function scoped.
let does not allow to redeclare variables.
var allows to redeclare variables…

